      }I connected my api key but its not lading the gif because the exercise.id parameter is incorrect. The exerciseName string should be mapped to the exerciseName value in the exerciseDB api and therrefore retrieving the right id to  search for the gif.Show more24 MarIdentified need to search API by name first, then retrieve ID for imageIdentified need to search API by name first, then retrieve ID for imageExactly right! You've identified the core issue. Here's the correct flow:
✅ Correct Implementation:
javascriptasync searchExerciseGif(exerciseName) {
  try {
    const rapidApiKey = process.env.RAPIDAPI_KEY;
    
    if (!rapidApiKey) {
      return null;
    }

    // Step 1: Clean the exercise name for better matching
    let searchName = exerciseName.toLowerCase().trim()
      .replace(/^dumbbell\s+/i, '')
      .replace(/^barbell\s+/i, '')
      .replace(/^cable\s+/i, '')
      .replace(/^machine\s+/i, '')
      .replace(/^band\s+/i, '')
      .replace(/^lever\s+/i, '');

    console.log(`🔍 Searching for: "${exerciseName}" → "${searchName}"`);

    // Step 2: Search ExerciseDB by name to get the exercise ID
    const searchResponse = await axios.get(
      `https://exercisedb.p.rapidapi.com/exercises/name/${encodeURIComponent(searchName)}`,
      {
        headers: {
          'X-RapidAPI-Key': rapidApiKey,
          'X-RapidAPI-Host': 'exercisedb.p.rapidapi.com'
        },
        timeout: 5000
      }
    );

    if (!searchResponse.data || searchResponse.data.length === 0) {
      console.log(`❌ No match found for: ${exerciseName}`);
      return null;
    }

    const exercise = searchResponse.data[0];
    const exerciseId = exercise.id;
    
    console.log(`✅ Found match: "${exercise.name}" (ID: ${exerciseId})`);

    // Step 3: Get the GIF using the correct ID
    const imageResponse = await axios.get(
      `https://exercisedb.p.rapidapi.com/image/${exerciseId}`,
      {
        headers: {
          'X-RapidAPI-Key': rapidApiKey,
          'X-RapidAPI-Host': 'exercisedb.p.rapidapi.com'
        },
        responseType: 'arraybuffer',  // Important: get binary data
        timeout: 5000
      }
    );

    // Step 4: Convert binary image to base64 data URL
    const base64Image = Buffer.from(imageResponse.data, 'binary').toString('base64');
    const gifUrl = `data:image/gif;base64,${base64Image}`;
    
    console.log(`🎉 GIF loaded for: ${exerciseName}`);
    return gifUrl;

  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`Error getting GIF for ${exerciseName}:`, error.message);
    return null;
  }
}
🎯 What This Does:
Step 1: Clean the exercise name

"Dumbbell Single Leg Calf Raise" → "single leg calf raise"
Removes equipment prefixes for better matching

Step 2: Search ExerciseDB API by name

/exercises/name/single leg calf raise
Returns: [{id: "1234", name: "dumbbell single leg calf raise", ...}]
Extract the correct ID

Step 3: Fetch the GIF using that ID

/image/1234
Returns: binary GIF data

Step 4: Convert to base64 data URL

Converts binary → base64 string
Creates data:image/gif;base64,... URL
This can be displayed directly in <img> tags!


